HEADWORD: Pelf
<hw>Pelf</hw> <pr>(p⟦ecr⟧lf)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>pelfir</ets> booty, OF. <ets>pelfre</ets>, akin to
<ets>pelfrer</ets> to plunder, and perh. to E. <ets>pillage</ets>. Cf.
<er>Pilfer</er>.]</ety> <def>Money; riches; lucre; gain; -- generally
conveying the idea of something ill-gotten or worthless. It has no
plural.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Mucky <xex>pelf</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Spenser.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧Paltry <xex>pelf</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Burke.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Can their <qex>pelf</qex> prosper, not got by valor or
industry?</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pelfish</ent>⟦br⟧
